1 (2) A person may operate a motor vehicle upon a bicycle lane when:
2 (a) Making a turn;
3 (b) Entering or leaving an alley, private road or driveway; or
4 (c) Required in the course of official duty.
5 (3) An implement of husbandry may momentarily cross into a bicycle lane to permit other vehi-
6 cles to overtake and pass the implement of husbandry.
7 (4) A person may operate a motorized wheelchair on a bicycle lane or path.
8 (5) A person may operate a motor assisted scooter on a bicycle lane or path.
9 (6) A person may operate an electric personal assistive mobility device on a bicycle lane or path.
10 (7) A person may operate a powered micromobility device on a bicycle lane or path.
11 SECTION 11. ORS 801.348 is amended to read:
12 801.348. “Motor assisted scooter” means a vehicle that:
13 (1) Is designed to be operated on the ground with not more than four wheels;
14 (2) Has a foot support or seat for the operator’s use;
15 (3) Can be propelled by motor or human propulsion; and
16 (4) Is equipped with a power source that is incapable of propelling the vehicle at a speed of
17 greater than [24] 20 miles per hour on level ground and:
18 (a) If the power source is a combustion engine, has a piston or rotor displacement of 35 cubic
19 centimeters or less regardless of the number of chambers in the power source; or
20 (b) If the power source is electric, has a power output of not more than 1,000 watts.
21 SECTION 12. ORS 814.512 is amended to read:
22 814.512. (1) A person operating a motor assisted scooter commits the offense of unlawful opera-
23 tion of a motor assisted scooter if:
24 (a) The person is under [16] 14 years of age; or
25 (b) The person operates a motor assisted scooter at a rate of speed exceeding [15] 20 miles per
26 hour.
27 (2) The offense described in this section, unlawful operation of a motor assisted scooter, is a
28 Class D traffic violation.
29
30 PROTECTIVE HEADGEAR REQUIREMENTS
31
32 SECTION 13. ORS 814.486 is amended to read:
33 814.486. (1) A person commits the offense of endangering a [bicycle] vehicle operator or pas-
34 senger if:
35 (a) The person is operating or using a [bicycle] vehicle on a highway or on premises open to
36 the public and the person carries another person on the [bicycle] vehicle who is under 16 years of
37 age and is not wearing protective headgear of a type approved under ORS 815.052; or
38 (b) The person is the parent, legal guardian or person with legal responsibility for the safety
39 and welfare of a child under 16 years of age and the child operates, uses or rides on a [bicycle]
40 vehicle on a highway or on premises open to the public without wearing protective headgear of a
41 type approved under ORS 815.052.
42 [(2) Exemptions from this section are as provided in ORS 814.487.]
43 (2) This section applies to the following vehicles:
44 (a) Bicycles;
45 (b) Motor assisted scooters;
[10]

A-Eng. HB 4007
1 (c) Electric personal assistive mobility devices;
2 (d) Powered micromobility devices; or
3 (e) Skateboards, nonmotorized scooters or in-line skates.
4 (3) The requirement to wear protective headgear under this section does not apply if
5 wearing the headgear would violate a religious belief or practice of the person.
6 [(3)] (4) The offense described in this section, endangering a [bicycle] vehicle operator or pas-
7 senger, is a specific fine traffic violation. The presumptive fine for endangering a [bicycle] vehicle
8 operator or passenger is $25.
9 (5) The first time a person is convicted of an offense described in this section the person
10 is not required to pay a fine if the person proves to the satisfaction of the court that the
11 person has protective headgear of a type approved under ORS 815.052.
12 SECTION 14. ORS 814.489 is amended to read:
13 814.489. (1) Evidence of violation of ORS [814.485 or] 814.486 and evidence of lack of protective
14 headgear [shall] is not [be] admissible, applicable or effective to reduce the amount of damages or
15 to constitute a defense to an action for damages brought by or on behalf of an injured [bicyclist or
16 bicycle passenger] operator, user or passenger of a vehicle or the survivors of a deceased [bicyclist
17 or passenger] operator, user or passenger of a vehicle if the [bicyclist or passenger] operator,
18 user or passenger of a vehicle was injured or killed as a result in whole or in part of the fault
19 of another.
20 (2) For purposes of this section, “vehicle” means the vehicles specified in ORS 814.486 (2).
21 SECTION 15. ORS 815.052 is amended to read:
22 815.052. (1) The Department of Transportation shall adopt and enforce rules establishing mini-
23 mum standards and specifications for safe protective headgear to be worn by people operating, us-
24 ing, being carried on or riding [bicycles, by passengers on bicycles and by people riding on
25 skateboards or scooters or using in-line skates] vehicles.
26 (2) This section applies to the following vehicles:
27 (a) Bicycles;
28 (b) Motor assisted scooters;
29 (c) Electric personal assistive mobility devices;
30 (d) Powered micromobility devices; or
31 (e) Skateboards, nonmotorized scooters or in-line skates.
32 (3) The rules shall conform, insofar as practicable, to national safety standards and specifica-
33 tions for such headgear.
34 SECTION 16. ORS 815.281 is amended to read:
35 815.281. (1) A person commits the offense of selling noncomplying [bicycle] protective equipment
36 if the person sells or offers for sale any [bicycle] protective headgear that does not meet the stan-
37 dards established by the Department of Transportation under ORS 815.052.
38 (2) A person commits the offense of unlawfully renting or leasing a [bicycle] vehicle to another
39 if the person:
40 (a) Is in the business of renting or leasing [bicycles] vehicles; and
41 (b) Does not have [bicycle] protective headgear approved under ORS 815.052 available for rental
42 for use by persons under 16 years of age.
43 (3) The offenses described in this section are Class D traffic violations.
44 SECTION 17. ORS 814.485, 814.487, 814.488, 814.534 and 814.600 are repealed.
