3 SECTION 18. Sections 19 and 20 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of the
4 Oregon Vehicle Code.
5 SECTION 19. (1) As used in this section, “storage battery” means:
6 (a) A rechargeable battery that supplies electrical power to the motor that propels a ve-
7 hicle and includes a replacement original equipment traction battery;
8 (b) A battery sold as part of a kit intended to convert a bicycle into an electric assisted
9 bicycle or a nonmotorized vehicle into a motor assisted scooter, electric personal assistive
10 mobility device or powered micromobility device; or
11 (c) A battery advertised as suitable for use with an electric assisted bicycle, motor as-
12 sisted scooter, electric personal assistive mobility device or powered micromobility device.
13 (2) A person commits the offense of improper sale or lease of a vehicle if the person:
14 (a) Sells, leases or offers for sale or lease a storage battery or charging system either
15 as part of or intended for use in a vehicle and the storage battery or charging system has
16 not been certified by an accredited testing laboratory as recognized by the United States
17 Occupational Safety and Health Administration, the United States Consumer Product Safety
18 Commission or an independent laboratory that has been certified by an accrediting body for
19 compliance with nationally recognized battery standards or other standards deemed suffi-
20 cient by the Department of Transportation; or
21 (b) Sells, leases or offers for sale or lease a vehicle or a storage battery or charging
22 system for a vehicle, unless a clear, legible indicia of the accredited testing laboratory de-
23 scribed in paragraph (a) of this subsection is permanently affixed on the vehicle or the
24 storage battery or charging system for the vehicle.
25 (3) The offense described in this section does not apply if the vehicle or storage battery
26 or charging system is being sold as used.
27 (4) The offense described in this section, improper sale or lease of a vehicle, applies to
28 the following vehicles only:
29 (a) Electric assisted bicycles;
30 (b) Motor assisted scooters;
31 (c) Electric personal assistive mobility devices; or
32 (d) Powered micromobility devices.
33 (5) The offense described in this section, improper sale or lease of a vehicle, is a Class
34 D traffic violation.
35 SECTION 20. (1) A person commits the offense of selling an impostor vehicle if:
36 (a) The person advertises, sells or offers for sale a vehicle:
37 (A) As an electric assisted bicycle and the vehicle does not fit the definition of an electric
38 assisted bicycle as defined in ORS 801.258;
39 (B) As a motor assisted scooter and the vehicle does not fit the definition of a motor
40 assisted scooter as defined in ORS 801.348; or
41 (C) As a powered micromobility device and the vehicle does not fit the definition of a
42 powered micromobility device as defined in section 2 of this 2026 Act; or
43 (b) The vehicle is designed, manufactured or intended by the manufacturer or seller to
44 be configured or modified to not meet the requirements or operate within:
45 (A) The requirements for the type of vehicle it is being sold, leased or offered for sale
[12]

A-Eng. HB 4007
1 as; or
2 (B) If an electric assisted bicycle, the class of electric assisted bicycle it is being sold,
3 leased, or offered for sale as.
4 (2) The offense of selling an impostor vehicle is a Class D traffic violation.
5 (3) In addition to any other penalty, a person that violates this section commits in an
6 unlawful practice under ORS 646.608.
7 (4) For purposes of this section, “configured or modified” includes any of the following
8 changes:
9 (a) A mechanical switch or button;
10 (b) A modification or change to the electric motor or the electric drive system;
11 (c) The use of an application to increase or override the electric drive system; or
12 (d) Any other means represented or intended by the manufacturer or seller to modify the
13 electric assisted bicycle, motor assisted scooter or powered micromobility device to no longer
14 meet the requirements or classification of the vehicle.
15 SECTION 21. ORS 646.608 is amended to read:
16 646.608. (1) A person engages in an unlawful practice if in the course of the person’s business,
17 vocation or occupation the person does any of the following:
18 (a) Passes off real estate, goods or services as the real estate, goods or services of another.
19 (b) Causes likelihood of confusion or of misunderstanding as to the source, sponsorship, ap-
20 proval, or certification of real estate, goods or services.
21 (c) Causes likelihood of confusion or of misunderstanding as to affiliation, connection, or asso-
22 ciation with, or certification by, another.
23 (d) Uses deceptive representations or designations of geographic origin in connection with real
24 estate, goods or services.
25 (e) Represents that real estate, goods or services have sponsorship, approval, characteristics,
26 ingredients, uses, benefits, quantities or qualities that the real estate, goods or services do not have
27 or that a person has a sponsorship, approval, status, qualification, affiliation, or connection that the
28 person does not have.
29 (f) Represents that real estate or goods are original or new if the real estate or goods are de-
30 teriorated, altered, reconditioned, reclaimed, used or secondhand.
31 (g) Represents that real estate, goods or services are of a particular standard, quality, or grade,
32 or that real estate or goods are of a particular style or model, if the real estate, goods or services
33 are of another.
34 (h) Disparages the real estate, goods, services, property or business of a customer or another
35 by false or misleading representations of fact.
36 (i) Advertises real estate, goods or services with intent not to provide the real estate, goods or
37 services as advertised, or with intent not to supply reasonably expectable public demand, unless the
38 advertisement discloses a limitation of quantity.
39 (j) Makes false or misleading representations of fact concerning the reasons for, existence of,
40 or amounts of price reductions.
41 (k) Makes false or misleading representations concerning credit availability or the nature of the
42 transaction or obligation incurred.
43 (L) Makes false or misleading representations relating to commissions or other compensation to
44 be paid in exchange for permitting real estate, goods or services to be used for model or demon-
45 stration purposes or in exchange for submitting names of potential customers.
[13]

A-Eng. HB 4007
1 (m) Performs service on or dismantles any goods or real estate if the owner or apparent owner
2 of the goods or real estate does not authorize the service or dismantling.
3 (n) Solicits potential customers by telephone or door to door as a seller unless the person pro-
4 vides the information required under ORS 646.611.
5 (o) In a sale, rental or other disposition of real estate, goods or services, gives or offers to give
6 a rebate or discount or otherwise pays or offers to pay value to the customer in consideration of
7 the customer giving to the person the names of prospective purchasers, lessees, or borrowers, or
8 otherwise aiding the person in making a sale, lease, or loan to another person, if earning the rebate,
9 discount or other value is contingent upon an event occurring after the time the customer enters
10 into the transaction.
