31 (2) Sixty percent of the amounts paid to the county treasurer under this section and under ORS
32 153.645 (4) and 153.650 (4) shall be deposited by the treasurer in the county treasury and may be
33 used only for drug and alcohol programs and for the costs of planning, operating and maintaining
34 county juvenile and adult corrections programs and facilities.
35 (3) Forty percent of the amounts paid to the county treasurer under this section and under ORS
36 153.645 (4) and 153.650 (4) shall be deposited by the treasurer in the court facilities security account
37 established under ORS 1.179 for the county in which the court is located.
38 SECTION 26. ORS 814.484 is amended to read:
39 814.484. (1) For purposes of ORS [814.485,] 814.486, 815.052 and 815.281, “bicycle” has the
40 meaning given in ORS 801.150 except that:
41 (a) It also includes vehicles that meet the criteria specified in ORS 801.150 (1) to (4) but that
42 have wheels that are 14 inches or less in diameter.
43 (b) It does not include tricycles designed to be ridden by children.
44 (2) For purposes of the offenses defined in ORS [814.485,] 814.486 and 815.281 (2), a person [shall
45 not be] is not considered to be operating or riding on a bicycle on a highway or on premises open
[18]

A-Eng. HB 4007
1 to the public if the person is operating or riding on a three-wheeled nonmotorized vehicle on a beach
2 while it is closed to motor vehicle traffic.
3
4 MILK TRUCKS
5
6 SECTION 27. Section 28 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of the Oregon Ve-
7 hicle Code.
8 SECTION 28. (1) The Department of Transportation shall establish a five-year pilot pro-
9 gram designed to test the allowance of commercial motor vehicles weighing not more than
10 129,000 pounds that transport fluid milk products on a limited number of highways in this
11 state. The department shall adopt rules specifying pilot program routes on highways in this
12 state where the department may issue permits for increased motor vehicle weights. In se-
13 lecting the routes, the department shall prioritize routes that utilize Interstate Highway 84
14 and:
15 (a) Connect to bordering states; and
16 (b) Connect to farms, milk plants, receiving stations or transfer stations for fluid milk
17 products.
18 (2) Notwithstanding ORS 818.010 and 818.020 and in addition to the exemptions allowed
19 under ORS 801.026 and 818.030, under the pilot program the department shall issue permits
20 that allow commercial motor vehicles hauling fluid milk products with a loaded weight of not
21 more than 129,000 pounds to operate on routes approved by the department.
22 (3) The department shall specify the conditions and terms of a permit issued under this
23 section.
24 (4) Applications for a permit under this section shall be made in a form and manner
25 prescribed by the department.
26 (5) The department, upon receiving satisfactory evidence of any violation of the limita-
27 tions of a permit issued under this section, may suspend or revoke the permit.
28 (6) The department shall periodically report back to the Oregon Transportation Com-
29 mission on the results of its monitoring and evaluation of impacts to safety, bridges and
30 pavement on all the designated routes within the pilot program.
31 (7) No later than September 15, 2032, the department shall prepare and submit a report
32 to the Joint Committee on Transportation and the commission on pilot program results. The
33 report must include:
34 (a) A comprehensive assessment on increasing maximum weight limitations under the
35 Oregon Vehicle Code;
36 (b) An infrastructure impact assessment detailing the effects of heavier vehicle weight
37 loads on bridges, pavement and highway safety, with a focus on high-frequency freight routes
38 in this state;
39 (c) An economic impact assessment quantifying the contributions of oversized freight to
40 Oregon’s economy, balancing potential economic gains from increased freight capacity with
41 the costs of infrastructure maintenance and safety considerations;
42 (d) An assessment of length as a factor for legal axle weights and alignment with lengths
43 allowed by the long combination vehicle freeze in federal law;
44 (e) An assessment of parking and staging infrastructure in this state for oversized loads;
45 and
[19]

A-Eng. HB 4007
1 (f) Recommendations supporting informed evaluation of increasing maximum vehicle
2 weight limits for divisible and nondivisible loads.
3 (8) The report described in subsection (7) of this section may include recommendations
4 for:
5 (a) Adjusting permit fees to account for highway maintenance needs;
6 (b) Identifying designated heavy-load corridors to minimize infrastructure impacts and
7 improve highway safety;
8 (c) Designating corridor connections to neighboring states that currently allow increased
9 vehicle weight limits for commercial motor vehicles as authorized under federal law;
10 (d) Updating the state transportation asset management plan;
11 (e) Changing weigh stations and weigh-in-motion systems;
12 (f) Adjusting bridge inspection plans and load-rating processes;
13 (g) Updating weight-mile tax rates and tables; and
14 (h) Collaborating with local road authorities.
15 (9) The department may adopt rules to carry out the provisions of this section.
16 SECTION 29. Section 28 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2033.
17
18 HIGHWAY COST ALLOCATION STUDY METHODOLOGY REVIEW
19
20 SECTION 30. Section 14, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special session), is amended to read:
21 Sec. 14. (1) In consultation with the study review team described in ORS 366.506, the Oregon
22 Department of Administrative Services shall undertake a review of the methodology for the highway
23 cost allocation study required under ORS 366.506.
24 (2) The department shall examine all aspects of the methodology for the highway cost allocation
25 study, including but not limited to the following:
26 (a) The revenues and expenditures included in the highway cost allocation study;
27 (b) How costs are allocated across different classes of vehicles;
28 (c) What constitutes a class of vehicle;
29 (d) The data used in the highway cost allocation study;
30 (e) The level of granularity to which cost responsibility is calculated for potential rate changes;
31 and
32 (f) Whether equity should be analyzed based on an estimate of the future biennium’s revenue and
33 expenditures or a retrospective analysis of past actual revenue and expenditures.
34 (3) The department may provide recommendations for updating the methodology for the study,
35 including any changes in statute needed to improve the outcome of the study and ensure fairness
36 and proportionate revenue and costs for each class of vehicle.
37 (4) The department shall submit a report in the manner provided by ORS 192.245, and may in-
38 clude recommendations for legislation, to the Joint Committee on Transportation no later than [June
39 30, 2026] March 15, 2028.
40 SECTION 31. Section 15, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special session), is amended to read:
41 Sec. 15. Section 14, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special session), as amended by section
42 30 of this 2026 Act, [of this 2025 special session Act] is repealed on January 2, [2027] 2029.
43
